notesStmt.note: This book of English heraldry was completed ca. 1589. The manuscript belonged to the Spencer family, as known through inscriptions on the first few flyleaves, including the motto "Dieu defende Le Droit" (God defends the right). This motto has long been associated with the Spencer family of England, which is the family line of Princess Diana, as well as the Spencers who were among the founders of Virginia. The Spencer family's heraldry is included in the manuscript, along with the coats of arms of numerous prominent British families, including the Hasting, Gray, Beuford, and Percye families. A similar book of English heraldry in the British Library, Stowe MS 693, was also completed at the end of the sixteenth century.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is English. The secondary language of this manuscript is Latin.

msItem.title: Heraldry
msItem.note: Heraldry of English rulers and related nobles; each section with description of name, lineage, and deeds of the earls, barons, and knights, followed by details of each escutcheon; complete but slightly misbound; fols. 1r-2v: nobles under William the Conqueror; fols. 3r-78v: nobles under William the Conqueror to nobles under Henry VIII; fols. 79r-80v nobles under William the Conqueror; fols. 81r-94v nobles under Henry VIII to Elizabeth I

support.p: Sixteenth-century laid paper; lozenge-shaped watermark composed of circles, most visible on front flyleaf v

supportDesc.foliation: Pencil foliation, upper right corners, rectos

collation.p: Undetermined None None Folios slightly out of order

layoutDesc.layout: Layout has no standardization due to the nature of the manuscript

handDesc.handNote: Elizabethan script; descriptions of the heraldry added in a seventeenth- or eighteenth-century hand

decoDesc.decoNote: Manuscript composed of 509 hand-drawn and painted armorials with accompanying inscriptions; armorials painted with blue, red, black, yellow; a deep ochre color has been used to mimic the effect of gold, but no true gold present; text in black ink; note: in order to retain the original information provided, images have been labeled with transcriptions of the titles given to the heraldry as they appear in the book

decoNote.title: Tudor family coat of arms
decoNote.note: The Tudor family coat of arms, as seen on the upper board, comprises many elements from the Tudor's heraldry. A quartered shield forms the center of the coat of arms, and a lion and unicorn stand to the right and the left of the shield. Above the shield is a knight's visor and gorget, which is topped by a crown. Hanging in the air above the crown are three images: a fleur-de-lis, lion upon a crown, and a dragon.

note.p: The inscription on the coat of arms reads both "ICH DIEN" (German for "I serve") and "HONI SOIT QUI MAL Y PENSE" (French for "Shame on him who thinks ill of it."

note.p: There is a discrepancy between the name under the shield, Thomas West, and the name by the shield, William West. William West, 1st Baron de la Warr, was attained for poisoning his uncle. Thomas West, 2nd Baron de la Warr, was part of Elizabeth I's Privy Council.

binding.p: Initially rebound in the eighteenth-century (somewhat out of order); current binding created in England, in mid-twentieth century; red leather with gilded crest of the current English monarchy on the upper cover; tooled decoration with gilt lettering on spine: "BRITISH COATS OF ARMS."

history.provenance: Likely created in England for William Spencer ca. 1589; his inscription on flyleaf iv: "William Spencer His Book;" manuscript stayed in Spencer family for some time, indicated by inscription on flyleaf v: "(?) Spencer 1633" accompanied by the Spencer family motto "Dieu defende Le Droit" (God defends the right)
Inserted eighteenth-century paper fragment discussing similar manuscript is dated and possibly initialed "8 July 1779. WW.," suggesting possible eighteenth-century ownership
